      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems with known analytical solutions must be reproduced within 1% for linear statics and contact problems representative of the pedicle screw geometry.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical benchmark suite includes Hertzian contact and cantilever beam cases. Results agree with analytical solutions within 0.4%. Code verification is current for the solver version used."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change of less than 5% between successive mesh refinement levels using Richardson extrapolation or GCI.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on the screw-rod-vertebral body assembly. GCI for construct stiffness QoI is 1.8%, for yield force 2.3%. Final mesh of 187 000 elements selected. Discretization error is within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual norms must converge below 1e-4 for all load steps; no unconverged increments permitted in the primary loading sequence.",
      "rationale": "All 240 load increments converge with force residual norm below 5e-5. No bisection or unconverged increments observed. Iterative solver tolerance is consistent with project requirements specification PRJ-REQ-2024-001 Section 4.3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments must be documented prior to result extraction.",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed by a second analyst not involved in original construction. Checklist-based review covers geometry import, contact definitions, boundary conditions, and material property assignments. No discrepancies identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model and contact formulation must be appropriate for large-displacement quasi-static loading of metallic implant constructs; justification must reference published literature or prior validation studies.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (Ti-6Al-4V, E=114 GPa, σy=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.1 GPa) is consistent with ASTM F136 material data and prior FDA computational studies. Augmented Lagrangian contact with friction coefficient 0.2 is appropriate for titanium-on-titanium interfaces. Model form is well-established for this device class."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric dimensions must be sourced from lot-specific coupon testing or certified material certificates traceable to the tested constructs.",
      "rationale": "Material certificates and tensile coupon data (n=5 per lot) provided by DePuy Synthes confirm Ti-6Al-4V properties within ASTM F136 limits. CAD geometry exported directly from the production design file. Dimensional measurements on three physical screws confirm agreement with nominal CAD within 0.02 mm."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test constructs must be production-equivalent; sample size must be sufficient to characterize experimental variability (CV < 15% for primary QoIs).",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot screws and rods. CV for construct stiffness is 6.2%, yield force 8.1%, force at 40 mm 7.4%. All samples are production-equivalent per DePuy Synthes quality records. Two independent laboratories provide environmental independence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must span the range of clinically relevant loading configurations; at minimum two distinct load offsets or fixture configurations must be evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 configuration (compression-bending, 60 mm offset). A second load offset was planned but not executed due to material availability constraints. Achieved level is below required; this gap is documented and accepted given that the single condition is the regulatory standard configuration and model predictions are conservative."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and loading must be demonstrated to reproduce the experimental fixture kinematics within 2% for displacement-controlled parameters.",
      "rationale": "Fixture compliance measured experimentally (3.1 N/mm) and incorporated into the FEA boundary condition as a spring element. Applied displacement profile in FEA matches crosshead displacement history within 1.4%. Equivalency confirmed by sensitivity analysis varying fixture stiffness ±20%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval must be below 1.96 for all primary QoIs; percentage difference must be below 10%.",
      "rationale": "E/uval: stiffness 0.84, yield force 1.21, force at 40 mm 1.07. Percentage differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 5.8%, force at 40 mm 4.6%. All three primary QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Validation uncertainty estimated per ASME V&V 20 methodology."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validated QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) must be directly linked to the regulatory submission claims regarding fatigue endurance and structural integrity.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield force are directly cited in the 510(k) substantial equivalence argument. Force at 40 mm displacement is the ASTM F1717 normative acceptance metric. All three QoIs are traceable to the device-level claims in the regulatory submission as documented in PRJ-REQ-2024-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation scenario must be geometrically, materially, and mechanically representative of the COU; any differences must be assessed for their impact on predictive validity.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs use the identical 7.5 mm non-cannulated screw geometry and production Ti-6Al-4V material as the COU device. ASTM F1717 test configuration is the standard regulatory surrogate for in vivo compression-bending loading. The validation scenario is judged highly representative of the COU with no material differences requiring correction."
    }
